			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I have scs3 too. If you get both a tash and a slow in before your pet aggros him, it'll take a round or two for him to get enough aggro to get it off you. If the pet is rooted and can't do it before the mob passes him, you'll have to make another pass. Or just hold off on slow (or tash) till he's engaged. The moment he's on the mob, you're not peeling aggro off him.
<br />

<br />
Another method is to time a root or a spin stun for when the mob will be in melee range of the pet. This works better in some places than others (mob melee range, line of sight). Personally, I hate having my pet rooted. I often get it a sow and make big use of guard. That way if the mob is between me and the pet, and the pet has to catch up to it, I don't have to kite in increasingly smaller circles til he hits it, he can just catch up really easy. Obviously, a sowed pet is more dangerous though.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, bottom line, try holding off on tash if you pull with slow, or hold off with slow if you pull with tash, till the pet is on the mob, and I think your problem will be fixed.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
